ok attempts to redress the balance by offering a fresh appraisal of James Stuart’s reign. Looking at both established and little-known plays and playwrights, Theatre and empire rewrites our understanding of the political and cultural context of the Jacobean stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aColonies in literature. 0aEnglish dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aNationalism in literature. 0aPolitical plays, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aTheaterzEnglandzLondonxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aEmpire.  aEngland.  aEnglish throne.  aGreat Britain.  aJacobean empire.  aJacobean.  aKing James VI.  aKing James.  aLondon stages.  aMiddleton.  aRowley.  aScotland.  aShakespeare.  aTheatre.  adrama.  adramatic material.  aearly modern history.  aforeign policy.  aplays.  apolitical culture.  apublic opinion.  astage.  atheatre companies.1 aMarshall, Tristan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526134738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526134738/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles